snippet.textDisplay: I had a no start on my mom's 2002 suburban recently. I tested everything, I was sure I was getting voltage everywhere based on my multimeter, starter was fine, fuses and relays were all fine. Also after sitting for a little while I noticed a severe parasitic drain on the battery because the voltage dropped down to like 6 volts. After trying a bunch of things back to back, I noticed that the negative battery terminal was hot, so I decided to test the voltage from the cables leading off the battery as the car was being cranked and the voltage dropped as soon as any load was placed on the battery and the terminals got HOT. turns out those old GM side posts are really poorly designed, because inside those rubber covers was absolutely filled with corrosion that I couldn't see upon my initial inspection! I mean I already disliked them for their tendency to strip out the threads on the battery, but wow. I cut off the covers, removed the bolts that screw into the battery, used a wire brush to clean up the lugs on the end of the factory cables, attached a 1 foot long battery cable with lugs on either end to each of the large copper factory lugs with a bolt and lock nut, then I popped some shrink tubing on to cover the connection between the old cables and new cables. I got her some top post terminal connectors and a different battery with top posts. Hasn't had an issue since and she now has top posts like most cars to boot.

snippet.textDisplay: 16:55 I tried depressurizing fuel lines like this on my 1998 ranger as I was changing my fuel filter. The lines still had pressure and when I disconnected the lines about half a liter of fuel sprayed me in the face, body and eyes (I was thankfully wearing safety glasses but that only helps so much). I am lucky that I could run inside and immediately start flushing my eyes out, otherwise it could have been much worse. The best way to depressurize if you can is to press in the schrader valve on the fuel rail while holding a rag against it. It is much more controlled. Stay safe!

snippet.textDisplay:
Really nice amigo Chris. You know i stopped using threadlocker, the reasons:


1. they cannot take heat for so long
2. (the main reason) threadlocker is a glue, and like any glue the surfaces to glue must be completely clean and you can tell how greasy or rusty the threads in a bolt can be.
So now i use then the old and simple pressure washer, it is made out of metal so heat is not a problem and i dont have to clean threads anymore.

take care.
